<Author>sitkom
<Content>A fab boutique hotel worth visiting! My husband and I recently returned from a two-week jaunt through Europe including London on the front and back ends. The trip included Spain, Switzerland and Sweden and I can tell you, hands down, that the Milestone was the highlight of the trip (and I'm hard to impress). The butler (Terry) is a scream, but in a proper, British sort of way. Since we were only there for one night at the beginning of our trip, we booked the least expensive room rate. Terry showed us our room, but then showed us a few other rooms that were available for an upgrade. While we loved this little tour, we decided not to upgrade as it was already late and we were getting up early to catch our flight. Our room was small and not as smartly decorated as the others we previewed, but the bathroom was large and nicely appointed. We had problems with the air-conditioning (the room was stifling hot) and it took the mechanics three tries before it was working again.We made our way to the bar (which had been recommended by family) and had it to ourselves. The bartender was top-notch and really knew his drinks (the best kir royal I've had to date) and I loved, loved, loved the quaintness of it (it's teeny tiny).When we left the next morning, I booked our return for two weeks later. When we returned and were escorted to our room I was jumping for joy when the door opened because they had upgraded us to a beautiful suite that I could have lived out the rest of my days in.We explained to the concierge what we were looking for in a restaurant for dinner and he nailed it with Ffiona's. Within walking distance of the hotel, everything about this place was perfect. The candles, the unpretentious food, the atmosphere (small, 15 or fewer tables), the hilarious proprietor, etc. Highly recommend.We'll definitely be back. Keep in mind, though, it's not for someone looking for a deal in a London hotel. This hotel is for travelers who can appreciate something different and better (and are willing to pay for it) than the typical mega hotel experience. 
